    "summary": "The Holy Roman Empire (formally established 962 AD when [[event:2932|Otto I]] was crowned emperor, though traced to [[event:2139|Charlemagne's coronation]] in 800 AD) was the dominant political institution of medieval Central Europe for over 800 years — a complex, decentralized confederation of German, Italian, Bohemian, and Burgundian territories whose emperor claimed to be the secular ruler of Christendom in partnership with the papacy. Voltaire famously remarked that it was 'neither holy, nor Roman, nor an empire,' capturing the gap between the institution's universal pretensions and its fragmented political reality.\n\nThe Holy Roman Empire's constitutional structure was unique: rather than a hereditary monarchy, the emperor was elected by the 'prince-electors' (initially three ecclesiastical and four secular princes, later more), creating perpetual tension between imperial centralization and princely autonomy. This tension — which the Investiture Controversy (1076–1122 AD), the struggle between Emperor and Pope over who could appoint bishops, brought to crisis — prevented the Holy Roman Empire from developing into a centralized state as France and England did. The result was that Germany remained politically fragmented into hundreds of princely states until 1871, while the empire itself survived (in increasingly attenuated form) until Napoleon dissolved it in 1806. Despite its political weakness relative to later nation-states, the Holy Roman Empire was the institutional framework within which much of European civilization — Gothic architecture, the Hanseatic trade league, the Reformation, and the Habsburgs' dynastic empire — developed.",
